      "reasoning": "Read the target config file to verify existence and current content. If the file is missing, note that it will need to be created. Ensure the directive `HostbasedAuthentication no` is present, uncommented, and set to `no`. Use `sed -i` to replace any existing line matching the pattern, or append the line if absent. The plan involves reading first, then applying the modification, and finally confirming the change.\n\nI\u2019ll check for the presence of `/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/00-complianceascode-hardening.conf` using `read_file`. If it exists, I\u2019ll run a `sed -i` command to replace any uncommented or commented `HostbasedAuthentication` line with `HostbasedAuthentication no`, ensuring the line is active. If the file lacks that line, I\u2019ll append it at the end. After modification, I\u2019ll set the file\u2019s permissions to `0600` with `chmod`. All actions will be performed via `run_cmd` and `write_file` as needed.\n\nRead the file first.  \nIf a line containing \u201cHostbasedAuthentication\u201d exists, replace its value with \u201cno\u201d.  \nIf no such line exists, append \u201cHostbasedAuthentication no\u201d to the end of the file.  \nBecause tool calls cannot branch, perform the replacement with `sed -i \u2026`.  \nThen run `grep -q HostbasedAuthentication` to test for the line\u2019s presence; if the test fails, execute `echo \"HostbasedAuthentication no\" >> file`.\n\nI first checked if the line \u201cHostbasedAuthentication no\u201d already existed in the SSH config file. I ran `grep -q` on the file and captured its exit code. If the exit code was non\u2011zero (meaning the line was absent), I appended the required line with `echo 'HostbasedAuthentication no' >> \u2026`. This two\u2011step approach avoids using a chained `||` command, which the tool does not support, and ensures the configuration is only modified when necessary.",
